Text.Value: I'd tell you another, but I'm afraid those are the only coins I've got for you. You should've come around sooner while I still had all three.
That's absolutely vile. Unsurprising of Zariel, but vile all the same.
A shit-eating grin. Oh, and uh. This. That's it.
Thanks. I'll put it to better use than Tiamat would have.
Leave.
That's it. Oh. And this slip of scratch. And now we're done.
First coin's got the soul of a woman named Mavery.

EditorData.NodeContext: MAH- vur-ee. Only here so pronounce it however you want.

Text.Value: You're the one set to consume his soul, I hear.
That's it.
What'd she tell you about me?
Thanks, Flo. Hearing all these stories has ruined my day, which I suppose was the point.
Didn't think to quiz her about her business.

EditorData.NodeContext: Laden with sarcasm; of course he isn't going to quiz a cambion.

Text.Value: The scud of her soul is yours, now.
Now why would she do a thing like that?
We won't be here much longer. Just waiting for the word to march. Better stock up while you can.
Fine. Get on with it, then.
That's a sad story indeed.
You can take a look at the rest of my lot, if you like. Got good weapons in search of a worthy wielder.
Whatever it is will be laden with strings attached. No thanks.
Thanks. I'll put it to better use than Tiamat would have.
Incredible. Flo must be livid I got out of Avernus. Wants to drag me back to the Hells with a few horror stories. All right. Go ahead.

EditorData.NodeContext: With a bit of a sneer. 'Flo' wasn't really her friend. More like Q and Picard.

Text.Value: That's it?
You know what devilfolk are like. No point trying to guess at why they do anything.
That cambion friend of yours went through a lot of trouble to get you them coins.
She got what she asked for. A fellow named Clint, destined to be her soul mate. Struck by a cart and died a few moments after clapping eyes on our Mavery. Poor guy.
Let's have the soul coins, then.
What was Flo doing here?
She was born to a cruel mother and a violent father and three evil brothers, all named Baldur.
I'm positive there's a catch here, but... go on. Let's see the coins.
Sure you will.
Get along, then.
Whatever you need to tell yourself, woman.
This'n has got the soul of a man named Frakes. Lived in a village near Neverwinter, hit hard by the worst hunger in a thousand years.
Did Flo have anything else for me?
For every coin you take, you've got to hear the story of the soul trapped inside.
Suit yourself. Then you won't want to know what she left you.
I don't want to hear another word about her or any other devil.
Then she handed me three soul coins. Said I could sell 'em if I wanted, but if I kept 'em for you, she'd consider it a favour owed.
Told me to look out for a one-horned tiefling with an infernal engine blazing out of her chest.
Let me see your wares.
Let me see your wares.
Zariel answered. Made old Frakes grow flesh upon flesh after flesh. His wee ones had all the meat they could stomach.
Ugh. Go on, then. What is it?
Well. Flo didn't tell a lie. She said you'd find me, and here you are. Karlach, isn't it?
I'd tell you another, but I'm afraid that's the only coin I've got for you. You should've come around sooner while I still had all three.
Flo?! What was she doing here?
We're just getting started.
She never knew a day of love in all her life. When she was a girl of fifteen, she sold her soul to Tiamat in exchange for someone who would love her unconditionally.
That's absolutely vile. Unsurprising of Zariel, but vile all the same.
Frakes called out for help - prayed for his children to have meat to eat.
Last one's got the soul of a little boy named Ongir. Eight years old. He liked playing in the sun with his friends. That's all I know.

EditorData.NodeContext: ON-geer but it's a one-off so do it your way

Text.Value: She came dressed as a novice. Gave me three soul coins. Said I could sell 'em if I wanted, but if I kept 'em for you, she'd consider it a favour owed.
You can take a look at my other wares, if you like. Won't entice Flo into my debt, but I'm always looking for wielders worthy of my stock.
Here it comes...
*Memories flood back of a cambion named Florenta you knew in the Hells. The closest thing you had to a friend.*
You got three soul coins out of the bargain, didn't you? I'd quit whinging if I were you.
That's it?
Leave.
'Fraid they're all gone. Should've come around sooner.
She gave me three soul coins. Said I could sell 'em if I wanted, but if I kept 'em for you, she'd consider it a favour owed.
I'm not falling for one of her little games. No thanks.
Didn't need to. Your one Flo did some devil woo-woo and stuck 'em in my head. Couldn't forget now if I wanted to.
No - I'm not playing her little game.
Next coin, please.
She said you might say that. And she said to let you have it your own way.
Leave.
Next coin, please.
Memorised 'em all, did you?
Sure. But she did have a condition.

EditorData.NodeContext: A condition before Karlach can have the soul coins

Text.Value: I'll put his coin to good use. He'll help me rid the Realms of people like Zariel.
I did my part. That means our business is done, unless you've got actual gold to hand.
Flo is such a rotten arsehole.
That's between you and her. Do you want the coins or not?

Synopsis: Karlach meets Lann at MOO and he offers her three soul coins as long as she hears the stories of their souls.
